<div id="node-328" class="node node-type-story node-promoted node-teaser build-mode-teaser"><div class="node-inner">

  
      <h2 class="title">
      <a href="/node/328" title="Article: Creating a Simple Spring MVC Web App with NetBeans 5.0">Article: Creating a Simple Spring MVC Web App with NetBeans 5.0</a>
    </h2>
  
  
      <div class="meta">
              <div class="submitted">
          Submitted by Colin Sampaleanu on Thu, 2006-08-17 08:11        </div>
      
              <div class="terms terms-inline"> in <ul class="links inline"><li class="taxonomy_term_6 first last active"><a href="/presentations" rel="tag" title="A link to a technical article about Spring" class="active">Technical Article</a></li>
</ul></div>
          </div>
  
  <div class="content">
    <p>This two-part article shows how to build a simple Spring MVC based web application, taking advantage of the NetBeans IDE. It walks through the creation of the project, the wiring together of views and controllers using Spring, and internationalization of messages in the application.<br /></p><ul><li><a target="_self" href="http://www.developinjava.com/readarticle.php?article_id=3">Creating a Simple Spring MVC Web App with NetBeans 5.0</a></li></ul><ul><li><a target="_self" href="http://www.developinjava.com/readarticle.php?article_id=4">Creating a Simple Spring MVC Web App with NetBeans 5.0 Part 2</a> <br /></li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p>  </div>

  <ul class="links inline"><li class="comment_forbidden first last"></li>
</ul>
</div></div> <!-- /node-inner, /node -->
<div id="node-326" class="node node-type-story node-promoted node-teaser build-mode-teaser"><div class="node-inner">

  
      <h2 class="title">
      <a href="/node/326" title="Article: Extend Your Type Transparently using Spring Introductions">Article: Extend Your Type Transparently using Spring Introductions</a>
    </h2>
  
  
      <div class="meta">
              <div class="submitted">
          Submitted by Colin Sampaleanu on Tue, 2006-08-15 16:01        </div>
      
              <div class="terms terms-inline"> in <ul class="links inline"><li class="taxonomy_term_6 first last active"><a href="/presentations" rel="tag" title="A link to a technical article about Spring" class="active">Technical Article</a></li>
</ul></div>
          </div>
  
  <div class="content">
    <p>In <a target="_self" href="http://debasishg.blogspot.com/2006/08/extend-your-type-transparently-using.html">Extend Your Type Transparently using Spring Introductions</a>, Debasish Ghosh shows how Introductions (aka Inter-type declarations or mixins) can be used via Spring AOP to add functionality to generic data access objects. The same technicque can be used with any class of code to allow some reusable functionality to be &quot;mixed in&quot; to another class or object.</p>
  </div>

  <ul class="links inline"><li class="comment_forbidden first last"></li>
</ul>
</div></div> <!-- /node-inner, /node -->
<div id="node-324" class="node node-type-story node-promoted node-teaser build-mode-teaser"><div class="node-inner">

  
      <h2 class="title">
